docs.abstract: House Democrats detailed an ambitious bill — including changes to ethics, campaign finance and voting laws — on Friday. But the ongoing the shutdown deflected attention.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Democrats unveiled on Friday the details of ambitious legislation devised to lower barriers to the ballot box, tighten ethics and lobbying restrictions and, in a swipe at President Trump, require presidents and candidates for the nation’s highest offices to release their tax returns.

headline.main: Aiming at Trump, Democrats Lay Out Agenda for a Post-Shutdown Congress
headline.print_headline: Not a Bill So Much as a Battle Cry for Democrats in the Next Election Cycle

docs.abstract: Responding to a warning from the secretary of state, Iran’s foreign minister said the U.S. was “in no position to lecture” about violating global deals after withdrawing from the 2015 nuclear deal.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo warned Iran on Thursday against launching three spacecraft in the coming months, describing them as a cover for testing technology that is necessary to lob a warhead at the United States and other nations.

docs.abstract: The Trump administration has touted increased energy exports as a key element in its strategy to rebalance foreign trade. It’s not working.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration has touted increased energy exports as a key element in its strategy to rebalance foreign trade. It’s not working.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States exported more oil and fuel than it imported last week for the first time in 75 years, a significant milestone in the resurgence of domestic energy production that comes as the Trump administration pushes to increase energy exports even further.

headline.main: U.S. Oil Exports Are Rising. So Is the Trade Deficit.
headline.print_headline: Trade Deficit And Oil Sales Rise Together

docs.abstract: President Trump’s suggestion that he could intervene in the arrest of a Huawei executive could put his sanctions enforcement strategy at risk.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s suggestion that he could intervene in the arrest of a Huawei executive could put his sanctions enforcement strategy at risk.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump suggested that he may intervene in the arrest of a Chinese tech executive, he was seeking to leverage her case into a win on trade. But law enforcement officials say the president’s comments could ultimately undermine America’s ability to enforce tough sanctions on Iran and other rogue nations.

headline.main: Trump’s Push for Trade Win Could Undermine Sanctions Enforcement
headline.print_headline: Peril Seen in Comment By Trump Tying Trade  To Huawei Extradition

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The report on the investigation by the special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III, will be made public on Thursday, and unless you’re a counterintelligence analyst, you may have lost track of how we got to this point in the saga and what Mr. Mueller was investigating in the first place. Here is a guide to what has happened over the past three years (yes, it’s been that long) and what we learned.

headline.main: Russia, Trump and Mueller: The Major Moments in the Case

docs.abstract: Rising rents and natural disasters have led to two straight years of modest increases in the number of people without stable housing, reversing years of declining homelessness.
docs.snippet: Rising rents and natural disasters have led to two straight years of modest increases in the number of people without stable housing, reversing years of declining homelessness.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Despite the booming economy, homelessness in the United States rose slightly for the second year in a row, with spikes in high-rent cities like New York and Seattle, according to an annual report released on Monday by the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

headline.main: Homelessness Rises Slightly Despite Strong Economy, Federal Report Finds
headline.print_headline: Spiking Rents Are Factor in Rise in Homelessness

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department asked a federal appeals court on Monday to throw out or at least temporarily halt a lawsuit that accuses President Trump of illegally benefiting from his family’s business, seeking to block more than three dozen subpoenas for documents from the Trump Organization, the president’s trust and other entities.

headline.main: Justice Department Asks Court to Halt Emoluments Case Against Trump
headline.print_headline: U.S. Asks Court to Halt  Lawsuit on Emoluments
